metadata.name: Turbulence #368
metadata.description:
Swirly shapes are rendered by passes of poisson samples of a warped noise field. The noise shifts with each pass, creating a layered effect. 

Dense editions may take over 2 minutes to draw fully.

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.

Press ’s’ to save a screenshot. Image size is 928x1200px
Press ’p’ to pause/resume at any time during the drawing.

Add '&size=#' to the end of the live view URL to render a not 1:1 variation of your edition at a resolution up to 3,000 px.

Common:
- 43 set palettes plus many more with combinations
- 3 color distribution methods
- 50/50 dark
- 50/50 monochrome with bright highlights 
- 3 drawing styles: lines, points, colored pencils
- 5 noises effects: full screen, distance from center, distance from bottom, horizontal center, vertical center, random circles, 3,5, or 7 horizontal and vertical bars
- Poisson point distribution based on set layers or the noise value

Rare
- 15% chance of a dark monochrome with gold strands

metadata.name: Hatching #34
metadata.description:
Hatching is one of the main techniques for pen and pencil drawings, etchings and copper engravings. Hatching is a combination of lines that thus depict different depths, effects and expressions. 

In pen and ink drawings, shading is indispensable. It is, in fact, the way to place the deep black ink on the mostly white paper. Hatching in architectural drawings indicates the various materials, for example in detail drawings. Look at old masters such as Duerer, Rembrandt and Da Vinci and you will see what depth they create with just carefully placed lines. 

In this generative abstract work I have not included any features, but some combinations do occur more frequently. Others are rarer. 

Chances:

Black pencil 50%
Red pen 10%
Blue pen 20%
Magenta 10%
Green pen 10%

Linen background 50%
Paper background 25%
Card board background 25%

Parallel hatching 50%
Cross hatching 50%

Rectangles 90%
Diamonds 10%

There is a small mathematical chance of a very special one, with his own drawing material.

metadata.name: Study of atom in analog, digital and A.I. #193
metadata.description:
Experimental generative collection that merges analog photography, AI, generative text, and algorithmic coding, by digging down into the essence and building blocks of the different artistic communication channels. 

This work engages with all aforementioned mediums in a joint manner, guided by a random process. It starts with a collection of analog photographs, shot on film and scanned that were later used as a training dataset in Generative Adversarial Network (GAN) training. This way, A.I. learns the main characteristics of film photography. In particular, it mimics its recognizable grain. Another type of pixel grain is added with the use of code and pixel shifting as well as digital manipulation. Finally, the last type of “grain” appears with the use of generative text where a different kind of A.I. was given a short description of the project and instructed to imagine the rest of the story. The fragmented and void of meaning parts of generative text are added to the images as one of the possible traits.

metadata.name: Patches #236
metadata.description:
This token generates a colorful abstract artwork that appears as watercolor on fabric. Project began as exploration of palettes used in famous masterpieces listed on Color Lisa web site. 97 color combinations used by great artists are applied here on abstract art.

Each piece is generated by bio inspired cellular automata in which colors from chosen palette are competing for domination on canvas. There are three different configurations of space fragmentation and each one is producing specific style.

metadata.name: Subdivisions #161
metadata.description:
As an artist with a background in engineering, I have always been a fan of technical drawings.
Architectural sketches and renderings fascinate me with their ability to visualize the conceptual.

I create generative art for the same reason - to reveal the beauty in an algorithm.

This project represents the division of space using techniques that, for me, call to mind sitting
at a drafting table, straight edge in hand, imagining what might be possible.

You can export a high resolution PNG (5000x5000) by pressing the 'e' key.

Twitter: @jeffpalmer
https://jpalmer.dev

metadata.name: Above (The Infinite) #195
metadata.description:
This project is an animated extension of my previous work in static generative tilings.
It explores how visual complexity can arise from the combination of simple building blocks.

This work is written in OpenGL Shading Language (GLSL) and requires a compatible GPU to function.

There are five features exposed:
- Palette: The color palette used (out of four possible).
- Palette Cycle: The color cycling method used.
- Phase Transforms: How many additional phase transformation functions are applied in addition to the core set of six.
- Blend Mode: How phase transformation are blended. Either strictly based on time or via a combination of screen coordinates and time.

The animation can be stopped and started by pressing the space key.

This is my genesis fx(hash) project.

Twitter: @jeffpalmer
Site: https://jpalmer.dev

metadata.name: Quantum Vacuum #357
metadata.description:
Empty space is not empty. It's filled with energy, transient fluctuations in quantum fields, bubbling with virtual particles popping in and out of existence. 

Part of an ongoing series of work combining my fascination with the fringes of fundamental physics, the emergence of complex behaviour through the interaction of very simple rules, and my obsession with hacking our perceptual systems. 

/Disclaimer: This is not a simulation, but an artistic conceptual interpretation and dramatization. :)
